\begin_layout Standard
The first operational ICF facility, known as Nova, was built at Lawrence
 Livermore National Laboratory (LLNL) in 1984.
 The facility employed 10 laser beams, each delivering 5 kJ of energy at
 the fundamental harmonic, which decreased to 2 kJ after third-harmonic
 conversion.
 Theoretical models and radiation hydrodynamics simulations predicted that
 Nova would deliver fusion reactions with neutron yields around 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{15}$
\end_inset

.
 However, the actual yield was a paltry 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times10^{13}$
\end_inset

 neutrons.
 Subsequent investigations revealed that the primary culprit was the degradation
 of the initially-spherical ablator shell by the Rayleigh-Taylor instability
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kilkenny1988"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In response to the limitations of Nova, a follow-on concept, the National
 Ignition Facility (NIF) was designed in the 1990s, also at LLNL.
 NIF utilized similar laser technology to Nova but on a much larger scale,
 featuring 192 beams, each delivering approximately 10 kJ of energy at the
 third harmonic.
 The facility first operated in 2009 and was expected to quickly produce
 fusion energy yields greater than unity (
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default
, more energy released from fusion reactions than deposited by lasers onto
 the target).
 Despite these expectations, the optimistically-named National Ignition
 Campaign concluded in 2012 without achieving ignition.
 It took 10 additional years of incremental improvement before ignition
 was finally produced during an experiment on December 5th, 2022, delivering
 approximately 1.5 times as much energy as was deposited in the target.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the process of developing a successful capsule design capable of producing
 ignition (similar to the schematic portrayed in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ICF_schematic_Zylstra"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), extensive research was conducted to identify, quantify, and minimize
 sources of unwanted mixing in the capsule.
 Although the influence of hydrodynamic instabilities was reduced compared
 to previous ignition efforts, investigators discovered that the symmetry
 of the shell was significantly degraded by several engineering components
 whose impact had not been previously apparent.
 These included the support tent used to suspend the fuel capsule, the fill
 tube used to inject cryogenic deuterium-tritium fuel into the capsule's
 interior, small imperfections in the crystal microstructure of the capsule
 shell, and other departures from the idealized spherical capsule form 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "weber_filltube,Clark2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In all but a handful of shots, the cumulative effects of these degradation
 mechanisms prevented the conditions at the core of the implosion from reaching
 and maintaining the areal density required for fusion-produced alpha particles
 to deposit significant energy on the surrounding fuel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When modeling capsule performance using radiation hydrodynamics codes, sources
 of ablator-fuel mixing can be broadly described as arising at either large
 or small perturbation wavelengths.
 In either case, the resultant mixing region can be initially described
 as consisting of bubbles of light material and spikes of heavy material.
 Over time, these structures develop into an anisotropic, inhomogeneous
 state, which may or may not be turbulent.
 Despite the high velocity (approximately 400 km/s) achieved during implosions,
 small length scales and significant plasma viscosity act to produce Reynolds
 numbers estimated to be on the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{3}-10^{4}$
\end_inset

 at peak compression.
 Present experimental diagnostics cannot image the small spatial scales
 (≤ 1 μm) which would characterize fully-developed turbulence, leaving the
 question unresolved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The central portion of the mixing region is the most statistically regular
 and has been thoroughly explored by theoreticians with support and confirmation
 by experiments and computations of the Richtmyer-Meshkov and Rayleigh-Taylor
 hydrodynamic instabilities.
 These investigations have provided valuable insights into the behavior
 of the mixing region and have guided the development of improved fusion
 capsule designs.
 However, the inability to directly observe and characterize turbulence
 at the small spatial scales involved in these processes remains a significant
 challenge for researchers in the field.
 Consequently, ongoing efforts in both experimental and computational domains
 aim to refine the understanding of the hydrodynamic instabilities and their
 impact on capsule performance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hydrodynamic instabilities driven by baroclinicity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The evolution of interfacial mixing between two fluids is largely driven
 by vorticity and can be described by the vorticity transport equation for
 a compressible fluid.
 Omitting enumeration of multiple fluid species, consider
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pdv{\vec{\omega}}{t}+\curl(\vec{\omega}\cross\vec{u})=\frac{1}{\rho^{2}}(\grad{\rho}\cross\grad{p})+\curl(\frac{1}{\rho}\div{\vec{\tau}})
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 is the velocity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\omega}=\curl\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 is the vorticity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are the bulk density and pressure, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\tau}$
\end_inset

 is the viscous stress tensor.
 Deposition of vorticity by shock and pressure waves is associated with
 the baroclinic production term, 
\begin_inset Formula $\grad{\rho}\cross\grad{p}/\rho^{2}$
\end_inset

, while the vortex stretching and diffusion terms 
\begin_inset Formula $\curl(\vec{\omega}\cross\vec{u})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\curl(\frac{1}{\rho}\div{\vec{\tau}})$
\end_inset

 drive the evolution and breakdown of the resulting vorticity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This work is fundamentally driven by the need to characterize and predict
 the behavior of shock-accelerated inhomogeneous fluids, an effort which
 predates the development of ICF with pioneering theoretical predictions
 by Richtmyer in 1960 and experimental confirmation by Meshkov a decade
 later 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Richtmyer1960,Meshkov1972"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The canonical initial condition under consideration consists of two stratified
 fluids of different densities, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{2}$
\end_inset

, which meet at a corrugated interface.
 Notably, many of the resultant phenomena are shared with the Rayleigh-Taylor
 instability, which can be viewed as a continuously-accelerated cousin of
 the impulsively-accelerated Richtmyer-Meshkov instability.
 A thorough review of recent investigation into both instabilities was conducted
 by Zhou 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zhou2017a,Zhou2017b"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In both cases, vorticity is deposited at the interface by baroclinicity.
 
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 misalignment between the interfacial density gradient and the pressure
 gradient.
 A linearized model of vorticity deposition allows for prediction of post-shock
 interface amplitude growth rates from initial conditions via algebraic
 gas dynamics, namely
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dv{\eta}{t}=k\varDelta\!VA\,\eta_{0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the sinusoidal perturbation's amplitude and wavenumber are given by
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, the shock velocity jump by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta\!V$
\end_inset

, and the interfacial Atwood number by 
\begin_inset Formula $A\equiv(\rho_{2}-\rho_{1})/(\rho_{2}+\rho_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 Given that the deposition process occurs as the shock wave is compressing
 the interface, there is some ongoing debate as to the suitability of the
 pre-shock 
\emph on
vs.
 
\emph default
post-shock values of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{0}$
\end_inset

, but fairly good agreement is found for most cases by taking the average
 
\begin_inset Formula $(A^{-}\eta_{0}^{-}+A^{+}\eta_{0}^{+})/2$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $^{-}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $^{+}$
\end_inset

 indicating pre- and post-shock conditions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Vandenboomgaerde1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In Meshkov's experiments, the initial shape of the interfacial perturbations
 was enforced by a thin nitrocellulose membrane , but the fragmentation
 of this membrane saps the strength of the shock wave and disturbs the post-shoc
k evolution of the interface.
 Additionally, the presence of a solid membrane presents severe difficulties
 for quantitative flow visualization techniques.
 As a result, subsequent workers have adopted a variety of membrane-free
 interfaces involving oscillating pistons, retractable corrugated sheets,
 vibrating walls, gas curtains, 
\emph on
etc.

\emph default
 
\end_layout

