\begin_layout Standard
Although the development of these interfaces is fully three-dimensional
 in all practical cases, certain important aspects of their evolution can
 be captured by the one-dimensional telegraph equation, which was classically
 used to describe the propagation and diffusion of signals in telegraph
 wires.
 Following Doss 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doss2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the analytical procedure begins with the Euler and compressible continuity
 equations for pressure 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, the fluctuating components of velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, and the mean and fluctuating components of the density, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\rho}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{\prime}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{Du^{\prime}}{Dt} & =-\frac{1}{\bar{\rho}+\rho^{\prime}}\grad{p}\label{eq:DossEuler}\\
\frac{D(\bar{\rho}+\rho^{\prime})}{Dt} & =-(\bar{\rho}+\rho^{\prime})\div{u^{\prime}}\label{eq:Dosscontinuity}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Multiplying 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DossEuler"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Dosscontinuity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 gives the ensemble-averaged transport equation for the velocity-density
 correlation 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\prime}\rho^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 This leaves several terms which must be closed by the assumption of a turbulent
 kinetic energy density 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, turbulent turnover rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, and a pressure-density correlation term 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\theta}$
\end_inset

.
 The result is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv[2]{\bar{\rho}}{\hat{t}}+\frac{\mu(n,C_{\theta})}{\hat{t}}\pdv{\bar{\rho}}{\hat{t}}-\hat{\nabla}^{2}\bar{\rho}=0
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{t}$
\end_inset

 is a nondimensionalized time and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\nabla}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the Laplacian operator in 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}=x/\lambda_{0}$
\end_inset

 nondimensionalized space, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}=\sqrt{k_{0}n^{2}/\Omega_{0}^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and a vortex decay constant 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $0<n<2$
\end_inset

.
 The late-time evolution of Richtmyer-Meshkov-like perturbations governed
 by the telegraph equation is entirely dependent on the damping parameter
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, where small-scale mixing corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu<1$
\end_inset

 decays to heat, while conversely, perturbations for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu>1$
\end_inset

 persist and continue to propagate.
 
\end_layout

