\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ideal inviscid vortex rings ought to propagate indefinitely due to the closed
 streamlines around the bubble of vortex-entrained fluid, but rings whose
 
\begin_inset Formula $Re$
\end_inset

 is sufficiently high to allow inviscid treatment invariably produce turbulent
 wakes into which the ring's momentum is shed while simultaneously entraining
 ambient fluid (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Instability-manifold"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 At lower Reynolds numbers, viscosity acts to diffuse vorticity from the
 vortex core region, increasing the effective size of the core at a rate
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv{a}{t}\sim\sqrt{\nu/t}$
\end_inset

 and thus enlarging the entrainment bubble.
 In both cases, the ring radius 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is found to grow steadily as circulation weakens.
\end_layout

